                  <acquisition>
                     
                     
                     
                     <p>Inscription by Edward Harley's librarian, <name type="person">Humfrey Wanley</name>, <date calendar="Gregorian">28 July 1725</date>. The Harley Collection, formed by <name type="person" role="owner">Robert Harley</name> (b. 1661, d. 1724), 1st earl of Oxford and Mortimer, politician, and <name type="person" role="owner">Edward Harley</name> (b. 1689, d. 1741), 2nd earl of Oxford and Mortimer, book collector and patron of the arts. Edward Harley bequeathed the library to his widow, <name type="person" role="owner">Henrietta, née Cavendish Holles</name> (b. 1694, d. 1755) during her lifetime and thereafter to their daughter, <name type="person" role="owner">Margaret Cavendish Bentinck</name> (b. 1715, d.1785), duchess of Portland; the manuscripts were sold by the Countess and the Duchess in <date calendar="Gregorian">1753 </date>to the nation for £10,000 (a fraction of their contemporary value) under the Act of Parliament that also established the British Museum; the Harley manuscripts form one of the foundation collections of the British Library. </p>
                     
                     
                     
                     <date>1753</date>
                  
                  
                  
